URL reference: https://www.fairwinds.com/blog/ai-infrastructure-runs-on-kubernetes-platform-ready
DateReviewed: 2026-07-13
Description: Our article today is going to talk about where AI workloads seem to be ending up, and whether your infra is prepared for those workloads. They give a bit of background - AI teams don't start on K8s; when they start, there are some local experiments. But after, they need compute and production level reliability, along with scaling - something Kubernetes handles well. Next, they talk about why K8s is the preferred choice - with training jobs needing bursty compute, inference needing to scale under load and recover on failures, and finally data and feature pipelines needing scheduling and observablility. The key thing is that AI workloads stress things differently, esp. with it wanting large amounts of GPU time. Getting data placement right is also critical, to avoid the constant need to ship data around. They have a compelling chart, where they list some of the nuanced differences and how a new approach is needed, esp. with GPUs. They talk about companies using a Hybrid approach, using public clouds for training and private clouds for the inference parts. They also mention companies are building on existing infra, extending their existing K8s clusters. They mentioned that with Platform engineering, we are seeing some abstracting away of the infra, to the point some devs don't see themselves as "K8s users" anymore. They say one danger is that the abstraction can mean while you are dependent on K8s, you don't fully understands what it is doing. They point out that bottlenecks can be infra related - like having available GPU capacity, but seems pinned due to poor scheduling. Great thinkpiece.
BottomLine: Very strong piece on how to approach using Kubernetes to run your AI workloads
