URL reference: https://x.com/sudiprokaya/status/2074158809803874723
DateReviewed: 2026-07-15
Description: Our article today talks about how people are structuring their AI approaches; not using a single model for all work, but rather using one model for decisions, another for volume requests and a third smaller one for the easy ones. Our authors argue that the router layer for AI should also act as an admission layer, with context, data perms, tools allowed, budget and when it needs approval. They argue the "request" has turned into the "delegated job" as a unit of software measurement. They consider the request "research this customer", and what that means practially - it could mean just reading notes, or it could be combining info from 5 disperate systems. And it's hard to manage from a governance perspective thinking about it like that. They point out that while a lot of agent tools are being run in production, it isn't always clear when AI is doing something, as opposed to a human making a request. They point out people have defined permissions, where often agents do not. They argue the true issue is an agent spending $400 on a $4 task. To solve this, our authors propose six gates that can guardrail AI actions. The gates are Identity, Workload class, Context, Tools, Approval, and finally the reciept. They argue this is the key piece, a summary of what the agent did, what it used, what it cost, and what the final result was. 
BottomLine: Very interesting discussion on approaches to AI controls
